data.name: micInstructionsLabel.Text
data.value:
If you don't know your input device's (microphone's) latency, then start here. First, choose an input device below.
Then click on the REC button (or press R) to start recording.
Watch the volume meter on the bottom right corner. If there's too much activity, you need to get to a quieter place in order to get accurate results. If the meter shows yellow or red spikes just from your ambient noise, then surely the results will not be accurate.
When you're ready, position your mouse as close to your microphone as you can and then click on the big button below with any mouse button. Be careful to not bump the mouse into the mic or make any other unwanted sounds -- after you click the button, the tool will be watching the recorded sounds and will pick up the first spike it detects.
In case your left mouse button click sound is not being picked up, remember that you can use other buttons (such as the middle mouse click, which is usually much louder).
If you like, you can click the button multiple times; The tool will calculate a rolling average over the samples.
When you're done, stop recording (either clicking on the REC button or pressing R again).

data.name: audioModeCombobox.ToolTip
data.value:
Whether to use Exclusive or Shared mode. Exclusive will usually give better latency than Shared. However, be aware that:
1) Applications rarely use Exclusive mode; Notably, games almost never use it. Morever, not all devices support Exclusive mode; and 2) Exclusive bypasses Spatial Audio, so if you want to compare the latency cost of enabling those, you'll need to use Shared.
Thus, if you're interested in knowing what is your specific device latency in a specific application, knowing whether that application is using Exclusive or Shared mode can help you get more accurate results.
If unsure, leave at the default.

data.name: label1.Text
data.value:
Choose the device you want to measure the latency of from the list below.
Then once again click on the REC button (or press R) to start recording.
Again, watch the volume meter for any unwanted noise. Ideally it should be always 0, or near 0, especially for this test.
This time around, when you're ready, place your speakers and microphone (or one of the earcups of your headphones, for example) as close to each other as possible -- once again, taking care not to cause any unwanted noise (such as bumping the headphones into the mic) -- and then click on "Start Sampling" below. The tool will play a few high-pitch, high volume sounds on your device and attempt to detect them. If no sound is detected, check whether the volume of your speakers or your microphone is not too low.
BE AWARE that the sounds played can be quite unpleasent; DO NOT click on "Start Sampling" while wearing your headphones or having your ears close to your speakers.
Wait for the tool to finish taking all the samples. You can check the results below.

data.name: micLatencyNumUpDown.ToolTip
data.value: This tool uses your microphone to measure the latency from your speakers. To get a more accurate result, it offsets that number from the measured latency. If you don't know the end-to-end latency of your microphone, then use the pane on the left to first calculate it.
